ed his talent as a highly skilled sketch artist and cartoonist. His output was prodigious and included regular commissions from The Graphic and various Japanese as well as French journals. He left Japan in 1899, never to return. The volume includes a full introduction of the life, work and artistry of Bigot by Christian Polak, together with an essay by Hugh Cortazzi on Charles Wirgman, publisher of Japan Punch. Wirgman was Bigot’s ‘predecessor’ and friend (he launched his own satirical magazine Tôbaé in 1887, the year Japan Punch closed). Georges Bigot and Japan also makes a valuable contribution to Meiji Studies and the history of both Franco- and Anglo-Japanese relations, as well as the role of art in modern international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDrawing, Frenchy19th centuryvCatalogs. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aAsian Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 7aART / Techniques / Painting.2bisacsh  apainting, cartoons, satirical magazines, history, changing face of japan.1 aCortazzi, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCortazzi, Hugh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPolak, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPolak, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060672040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781898823766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781898823766/original  a978-3-11-060672-0  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles